1 Imagini, chi bene intender cupe 2 quel ch’i’ or vidi—e ritegna l’image, 3 mentre ch’io dico, come ferma rupe—,
4 quindici stelle che ’n diverse plage 5 lo ciel avvivan di tanto sereno 6 che soperchia de l’aere ogne compage;
7 imagini quel carro a cu’ il seno 8 basta del nostro cielo e notte e giorno, 9 sì ch’al volger del temo non vien meno;
10 imagini la bocca di quel corno 11 che si comincia in punta de lo stelo 12 a cui la prima rota va dintorno,
13 aver fatto di sé due segni in cielo, 14 qual fece la figliuola di Minoi 15 allora che sentì di morte il gelo;
16 e l’un ne l’altro aver li raggi suoi, 17 e amendue girarsi per maniera 18 che l’uno andasse al primo e l’altro al poi;
19 e avrà quasi l’ombra de la vera 20 costellazione e de la doppia danza 21 che circulava il punto dov’ io era:
22 poi ch’è tanto di là da nostra usanza, 23 quanto di là dal mover de la Chiana 24 si move il ciel che tutti li altri avanza.

query.result:
1 Imagine, whoever wishes to understand well 2 what I now saw—and retain the image, 3 while I speak, like a firm rock—,
4 fifteen stars that in different regions 5 the sky quicken with so much serenity 6 that it surpasses every composition of the air;
7 imagine that chariot to whose breast 8 is enough of our sky and night and day, 9 so that at the turning of the time it does not diminish;
10 imagine the mouth of that horn 11 that begins at the tip of the stem 12 to which the first wheel goes around,
13 having made of itself two signs in the sky, 14 as did the daughter of Minos 15 when she felt the chill of death;
16 and the one to have its rays in the other, 17 and both to turn in such a way 18 that the one goes to the first and the other to the next;
19 and it will have almost the shadow of the true 20 constellation and of the double dance 21 that circled the point where I was:
22 after it is so far from our custom, 23 as far from the moving of the Chiana 24 moves the sky that advances all the others.

28 Completed the singing and its turning measure;
29 and turned to us those holy lights,
30 felicitating themselves from care to care.

52 That which does not die and that which can die 53 is nothing other than the splendor of that idea 54 which, loving, gives birth to our Lord;
55 because that living light which so measures 56 from its shining, which does not separate 57 from him nor from the love that unites them,
58 by its goodness gathers its radiating, 59 almost mirrored, in nine subsistences, 60 eternally remaining one.

